[1]
Date: Mon 21 May 2007 18:17:41 +0100
From: Ian Brown
<i.h.brown@vla.defra.gsi.gov.uk>

Re: PRO/AH> Avian influenza, poultry vs migratory birds (24); UK -
tests could miss bird flu in migratory birds
------------------
In response to the suggestion that the UK could be missing bird flu
in migratory birds I wish to make the following comments and observations:
UK programmes for the detection of H5N1 HPAI are highly optimised based upon
i) targeting dead birds
ii) examination of tissues not swabs (tissues have been shown to be
superior for detection of this virus).
Data at EU level during the last 18 months has unequivocally shown
this to be the most sensitive and reliable approach for detecting
early incursion of H5N1 HPAI in wild birds. The study cited (PLoS
Pathogens, DOI:10.1371/journal.ppat.0030061) failed to detect H5N1
HPAI in healthy birds (as we have in the UK) but this is not
unexpected based upon the results of the European programme as a
whole. Dead birds represent one strand of our surveillance with
others examining live healthy birds.
There is no evidence of any difference in the sensitivity of the
methods used by ourselves and those in the study quoted to explain
the difference in the apparent crude prevalences in the UK, Sweden
and The Netherlands combined. One does not expect a similar
prevalence or presence of infection in all countries nor a constant
presence or prevalence of infection over time. It is therefore
misleading to say that "on average 6 percent of ducks in Europe are
infected with influenza A viruses." The study was restricted to
Sweden and The Netherlands and there are a number of species of ducks
for which the apparent prevalence varied considerably. Direct
comparisons between different surveillance programmes are unsafe
since they do not take account of the factors and variation that may
influence the presence and detection of influenza A viruses such as
the sampled population, temporal and geographic factors.
The UK has taken the lead in implementing a targeted programme of
surveillance in wild birds aimed at detecting the 1st incursion of
H5N1 HPAI in areas if there may be intimate contact with poultry. The
design has taken account of a number of factors including higher risk
species of migratory bird for introduction of virus, population
density of these species in relation to that of poultry production
where poultry holdings are ranked according to risk of incursion.
These factors provide a map of where virus incursion into poultry is
thought most likely to occur and surveillance efforts are enhanced in
these areas.
--
Communicated by: Ian Brown
Director of EU/OIE/FAO International Reference Laboratory for Avian
Influenza
VLA-Weybridge
UK
Veterinary Laboratories Agency (VLA)
